@6051 = ~The Ugly Stick~
@6052 = ~Staff +4: The Ugly Stick

"The Ugly Stick" combines a Staff Spear +2 with the Staff of Rynn +4. At first appearance, it is not a particularly subtle recrafting. It is properly known as The Staff Pike of Ryn, but no one really bothers. For all intents and appearances, a staff spear was sawed in half with the two sharp ends on the end of the Staff of Rynn and bolted together with an iron sleeve that double as grips for this weapon. Obviously this was the first time anyone ever requested an item like this, and probably the last. It's one redeeming value is that it's cheaper than a Rod of Lordly Might.

What it lacks in craftsmenship, it makes up for in effectiveness. By taking two bastard swords +1, chopping them out of their hilt and reforging their blades, the weapon may be used for both spearing an enemy or slashing. Otherwise the wielder can just whack an enemy with the staff normally. Such an item is useful for those 'oppurtunities' to fight various opponents, when some are resistant to one type of damage but vulnerable to another. 

Whether by chance or design, the weapon's designer made it balanced enough to throw and enchanted it return to the user; it is known to tumble and do varying damage however. Some minor elemental magics were also worked in to retain the pretense of possibly being a Mage's or Cleric's staff. The staff may be used to cast 'Burning Hands' four times per day; best used to kill downed trolls and light camp fires on a wet night. In a pinch, it also makes an excellent cane fishing pole. The powerful enchantment apparently attracts trout and other game fish, oddly enough.

Whomever crafted the weapon purposely left off any identification marks and lore masters would simply remember it as the 'Ugly Stick' from Amn. In the adventuring trade in southern Faerun, it would become an adventuring in-joke to kid an ugly, dirty or poorly equipped adventurer by saying they had been beaten by 'The Ugly Stick'. Detractors aside, The Ugly Stick was an excellent fishing pole. 

